Excercise 3.3.1
1. It’s missing a close parantheses so the color is being specified in the wrong spot
2. When you run MPG you can see the variable type above each column, etc. In this data set class, fl, drv, trans, manufacturer, model are chr, and numberical variables are displ, year, cyl, cty, hwy


ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = class, size = cyl, shape = fl))

Aesthetics behave differently - for example I couldn’t assign a shape to a continuous variable. Size was not advisable to be used for categorical data.


  1. It lets me do it and the legend is combined automatically!
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = fl, shape = fl))

  1. The stroke adds a border around a shape. Shapes 21-24 can have a border
  2. It turns it into a boolean expression - so true or false, very cool!
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = displ < 5, shape = fl))

Excercise 3.5.1 4. Faceted data makes it very clear what you’re looking at for each characteristic you’re examoing, so in this case the model of the car. But the color is better if you want to look at the trend in data all together. Pros and cons. With a huge amount of data, it could be hard to see the individual patterns without faceting. 

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow = 3)

  1. nrow specifies how many rows of mini, faceted graphs a grid should have. Ncol does the same but for columns. You can also scale, shrink, add labels, switch labels, change the direction. Facet grid is better for when you have 2 discrete variables and all combinations of the variables exist.
